segments.text: from Hawaii, from storage in Oakland, from Homestead where my last duty station in the states were.
And we were able to do that.
And then after that you had one year, you could have one free move and one government expense within the next year, within one year period after you retire.
And I retired on
on the first of September.
Well, our youngest daughter, we thought we were going to get a job up in Denver, take a job up in Denver, so she enrolled in the University of Colorado to be close at home.
So she had to go up there, be there by the 31st of August.
So I got my retired papers and the retired identification and what have you.
ahead of time so when I actually retired I was approaching Lowry Field in Denver where we were staying to deliver our daughter up to college.
And so I went over to the BX and the base exchange to get a check cashed and they said oh we don't, the same day that I retired some guy said oh we don't cash checks for retired people here.
And I said, well, I'll go to the officer's club.
Well, no, the officer's club didn't retire, didn't cash checks for retired people either.
And boy, just one day you can cash a check anywhere in the world, the next day you couldn't cash a check on base.
So...
So that really shakes you up.
I mean, that really shakes you up.
Especially after you've lived 30 years as a volunteer.
Yeah, that's right.
And so I called up the base commander up there.
He was a friend of mine.
He graduated, I guess, a couple of years ahead of me at West Point.
And he was a major general up there.
So I called him up.
And I said, Chuck, what goes on here?
I can't even get a check cast.
Oh, he says, we have so many bounce checks from retired people, why we just have to stop this.
Bounce checks from retired people?
That's what he said.
How can that be?
Well, they go into the transit, well, he said transit retired people.
They're traveling around the United States, and they stop at an air base and cash a check, and the doggone thing bounces.
Mm-hmm.
For various reasons.
You know, you're retired, your checking account's not fully moved, and all of a sudden your pay is involved, getting to you on time.
So what did the commander say?
Oh, he said, go back to the officer's club, and I'll call them up and clear it for me.
Clear it with them so that you can cash the check.
Well, yes, that solves the problem.
But it's really a shock at that time.
And then your other problems that you have in retiring, you're being in very responsible jobs, and you're a really capable individual.
And this applies to a lot of people in the military.
And then they go out and looking for a job, and no one in civilian life can equate the job you did in the military to a job
that they have available in the industry or the educational field or what have you.
I was interested in getting into a university.
And teaching?
Teaching or being an administrative assistant or comptroller in the administrative field.
Not necessarily in teaching.
You can get a job in teaching.
having had a master's degree and all the experience.
They were willing to give me a job in teaching.
Who was this?
Well, I went to see President of the University of Houston, President of Tate at SMU.
I wrote to the
the various college associations in the southeast.
I went up to the University of Texas and talked to the president up there.
But they really weren't interested.
Here you are, 55 years old.
They said, we're interested in a guy that's 25 years old who has a future.
I'll just face it.
You are 55, and 10 years, you're going to have to retire anyway, all over again.
So we take you two years to train you.
We only get eight years of productivity out of you.
Whereas here's a young man.
that we train in for two years, we have twenty-five years or thirty years of productivity.
That must have really been frustrating for you.
Oh yeah, well.
And then you got into the job corps program and you said, well, they won't even interview you.
So you started working at banks.
I said, well, I'll take that.
being an executive of a bank, why you should be able to get a job in the bank, being a loan officer or something of this sort.
Well, you know, the banks won't even talk to you.
The only thing that you would get through the banks is companies that they had big loans with that were having problems of paying them.
They want you to go out and collect.
Yeah, no, they want you to go out and get in there and get the things straightened out so that the outfit won't go bankrupt and protect their investment.
And you don't blame them.
So you were depressed.
Yeah, you're depressed.
What were your feelings when you left Hawaii, which was your last post?
Well, I mean, I was...
I was, I mean I didn't, being the fact that you weren't going to get promoted by, I was ready to retire and try something new.
And you figured with the experience you had you should be able to get a pretty good job.
And you were offered, I guess I was offered
at the time as good jobs as you expect, except you probably expect more than people really willing to give you as an unknown.
The National Security Agency has some contracts for some cryptological
equipment that they had a company that was way behind in production and of course they knew me so they were promoting me to go into that company and take over the production part of it.
And I could have gotten that job.
Why didn't you take it?
Where was it?
It was in Maryland.
in around Baltimore, Maryland someplace.
Well, you went up and talked to the President, of course the National Security Agency didn't have a lot of leverage.
And they said, yeah, we'll give you a job, you'll be the executive assistant of Mr. Brown.
And then you look at Mr. Brown and maybe he's twenty-five years old.
He said, well, can I work for him?
I mean, you have to look at it as being his administrative assistant.
Well, looking back, that's the only way that you probably could get a job, starting out as an administrative assistant.
And then after showing your colors over a period of a year or so, you'd fit into the management side.
But when you're retiring, and when you retire in positions without help,
why you were just in a hurry.
You just weren't particularly interested in starting out at $18,000, $20,000 in a low-level job.
The pay was all right.
Looking back, you'd probably say, OK, I'll just give you six months for free.
I'll just live off my retired pay in six months.
And then at the end of six months, we'll be able to decide what job I can have and what the pay will be and what the benefits are.
So then I worked at this retirement thing.
rather thoroughly.
Do you think your disappointment at these low level offers and the fact that you had been commander of a lot of responsibility, is this the reason why you decided to build your own company?
Well I decided I was going to want to get involved in a small company and of course we had
not a lot of savings.
You don't make a lot of money in the military.

And as I would say that we had bought real estate and when I retired I think we had three houses that one of them was paid off and worth about $15,000 and we had one in Washington that was oh we probably had another $15,000 equity in it.
So you ended up raising maybe $35,000 or $40,000 but
you also had two dollars in college and that was taking around $15,000 a year out of your savings.
So I figured that I had about $15,000 to get into a small company.
You should talk to my wife about our searching for small companies because we went to Del Rio and we advertised in Wall Street Journal.
And we got a lot of replies of companies that were interested in selling out.
And we had a, there was a bottling company, a PepsiCo bottling company in Del Rio that was supposed to be making a lot of money and very good.
But you go down and look at it and the guy owner was living in a trailer on the site.
You look at the equipment and it was very obvious it was maybe
thirty, forty, fifty years old and you had dirty balls all over the place.
It just didn't give you the impression that it was a very lucrative place to come to take over.
Then we went over to some small company manufacturing horse trailers, cattle trailer, horse trailer type of thing.
And they were willing to sell out for about forty thousand dollars and of course you looked them over and you really weren't very impressed.
It was a little small town about fifteen hundred people that they were building and they were building good product but supposedly they were selling horse traders from here to Florida.
And so we didn't, weren't impressed there.
And then we went up to another balling company in Temple, Texas and that was a pretty good looking company.
Orange Crush I think it was.
And they had Delaware Punch I think was another.
And that wasn't too impressive.
But are these the typical types of problems that a general will have when he retires, do you think?
Well, I think that you have two, no, you probably have two different types of problems.
One of them is the general is not going to, don't expect to do anything.
The general himself doesn't expect to do anything?
Yeah, he doesn't want to do anything.
I mean, just like a friend of mine who was, who was,
Oh, I guess he was five years my senior.
He retired in Austin.
Well, the first thing he did was go to enroll in the University of Texas to get the VA benefits.
I think he just took any courses, the easiest courses there.
But so he runs his VA benefits out on that.
Well, by this time, he was...
62 or what the minimum age to get Social Security.
So he starts drawing Social Security.
So he gets his retired pay plus Social Security.
He draws his GI Bill.
And so I wrote him a letter when I was getting ready to retire and asked for his suggestion.
He said, well, do nothing and wait around all day for 4 o'clock for cocktail hour.
And obviously Anthony said, well the first year he started drawing Social Security, he drew all that he had ever paid in there.
So since he was sixty-four, why he had been a freeloader on the Social Security system.
To me this is a
is stealing almost.
Although I agree he's due it, but that's not really what Social Security was set up for.
So that's the first problem, people who the general just looks out and says, well, I'm not going to do anything.
And the other problem is someone like you who wants to do something but cannot find a job.
They really cannot find a job.
Then, of course, you have certain other selected general officers who
who have been in contact with the big industrial complexes that get a job with the companies with whom they've been dealing.
Sure, there's a number of generals and admirals who work for Boeing and General Dynamics.
And Bell and all this type of thing.
And I got in contact with some of those people.
And some of them are happy and have a very responsible job, and others were hired just because they knew who they knew in the Air Force or who they knew in the military.
And they were real unhappy with their jobs that they were doing, although- They were basically contact men to try to influence the current leadership in the military to buy their goods.
That's right.
And you're in a poor position because see according to the regulations and rules and regulations it says a regular retired officer that you can't have a job that requires you to contact these people.
Now they can come out to see you and I presume there's some
some communication between them whether or not it's legal or not legal.
But the fact that General Jones is working for Northrop why then you would not contact him or if you went out to visit that particular company why you'd probably go out and have
cocktails with him and things of this sort.
I mean it's just a natural set up.
But it's retiring from one career to the next is I would say quite shocking.
Because you don't know, it's one of these unknowns.
You're at a 55-year-old age.
You have a wife and kids to take care of.
You have a retired pay that's, I'll say, about half of what you were getting on active duty.
And although financially, I was in a pretty good position.
I should have probably just sat around for six months and let the world go by and start out then, but I was in a hurry.
Well, let's stop here.
All right.
Now you've been in positions of leadership in the military and in civilian life right now.
Could you, I know that you've
talked on this.
Like you told me earlier, you've given speeches on leadership before.
You have Air Force manuals on it.
You have a whole file cabinet on it.
Could you just give me a definition of leadership?
Well, I think it's the ability to get people to work for you.
You read your Air Force manual real well then because that's what it says in here too.
It says, Leadership is the art of influencing people to progress with cooperation and enthusiasm toward the accomplishment of a mission.
That sounds like very good.
Do you think that there's a difference between leadership in civilian and in military?
Well, I think that your leadership in civilian industry is designed more of an objective of making money, either for the stockholders or what have you, than in the military.
I mean, I think your military isn't a profit motive at all.
I think the motive is to get the most bang for a buck.
This is what your objective is as far as the military is concerned, is to keep the cost down, but to get the people enthused and do a better job.
If you do that, then you're not paying the guy anymore.
You're just getting a better job out of it.
In the military, we have had some rather flamboyant leaders, dramatic leaders in the last 30 years.
George Patton, people like this, the tough sort of, I suppose General MacArthur was in a sense like that.
Tough leader out in front of his troops over the hill, sort of, come on guys, we'll kick you in the back seat of the pants and let's go.
Do you feel that that type of leader is more typical in the military or other types of leaders, more of a manager type leader?
Well I would say the Eisenhower type leader is a more typical type of military leader.
Patton of course, he had showmanship and I tell you his people followed him although he got into lots of
trouble of slapping kids in the hospital and this type of thing, but as far as the people that were in a Patton outfit, they had nothing but glory for Patton because he knew how to get the job done.
People just followed him.
They knew that he was going to protect them.
What kind of leader was Curtis LeMay?
Well, John LeMay was, I think, the same type of leader.
He demanded perfection, and he got perfection.
The guys who couldn't produce, well, he just got rid of them.
He was brutal that way.
However, only at the same time, he had a tremendous amount of compassion for the families, for the feelings of his people.
was the type of leader that you knew he had to produce for.
But at the same time, you knew that he was going to take care of your family if you got caught overseas.
And that's a  and I think that he really could get the job done, too, probably a lot faster than Eisenhower could get it.
What kind of leader were you?
Well, I don't know.
I think I was more of the quiet type of leader.
However, it's just like going to the military academy.
If you studied hard the first six weeks of a semester and you got in a high grade, a high class,
why then you normally made good grades there on.

I think when you went into a base and you got real mean the first six weeks or two months or three months and then after that why then you could just relax and everything just went along real smoothly.
As you know that they knew you meant business.
Yeah and that you were still human and what have you.
So you still had to take care of people
Because all your, whether or not you're in civilian life or in military, you have to get the job done through influencing people.
Okay.
You said before that a couple of the values that a leader should have is positive attitude and enthusiasm.
What are some of the other values that a leader should have?
Well, I would say you're going to have to have ideas, you have to have creativity.
and you have to make decisions and you have to get results.
And you do all of that through people.
And this creativity is a talent.
I think you can develop it, but you
There are so many people that don't look at a situation critically.
They'll look at it through rose-colored glasses.
I used to take my bunch of second lieutenants out around the school buildings and they couldn't see a cigarette butt on the ground.
They just didn't see it.
They just looked beyond it.
Whereas I could see the cigarette butts on the ground so that you could keep the place clean.
And I think that you have to look at a situation critically in order to improve the situation.
And you try to develop that capability, but a lot of people just don't, just can't
Look at the situation critically.
The enthusiasm, I just think that enthusiasm, if you are exuberant in enthusiasm, it's catching.
I think the other thing you have to do is be able to tell people, communicate with people as to what you want done.
Because you can have the most brilliant ideas that you
that you can find.
But if you can't get people to communicate with people to get the job done, you still won't get the job done.
Sure.
In the military, how important is tolerance and flexibility?
Well, in some cases, you just can't have flexibility and tolerance now.
Just like I mentioned,
If an individual is taking an emergency test and flying an airplane, as far as I'm concerned, there's no tolerance there.
If it means the difference between him living and dying or the maintenance of his aircraft, there's no tolerance.
It has to be perfect.
But when you get away from those situations where it really doesn't make any difference, why, then you can
very easily ask, what do you think?
And then he says, well, I would do it this way.
Well, if it's as good a way as yours, you're a lot better off by saying, okay, that sounds good.
We'll do it that way.
And in that situation why you always let him advance his ideas and if his idea is equal to yours or
Or you can certainly say, well, that sounds good, but how about adding this to it?

So you maybe modify his a little bit and then it's his idea, then he will do it a lot more willingly and say, and it would be if you say, I want it done this way and I want it done now, then he'll do it, but he'll probably resent for it a little.
In other words, use that individual's ideas.
Oh, yeah, well.
This is a technique that we use in the technical schools when we're in the headquarters.
We'd have the bases come in with their plan, and if we could accept them, we'd accept their plan.
And then you would have no problem with getting the thing implemented.
But if you went down with a directive, say, I want it done this way, this is what you'll do.
Well, they might do it, but they still won't get it done as easily.
But we always let them present their plan, and if it was
acceptable even with smaller modifications, well you accept it.
So you're a lot better off in having them present their plan, approve their plan, and they go back happy and they came up with a good job.
It's very easy to do.
Let's say you were going back to Texas A&M next week and you were asked to give a lecture to these 18-year-old
18-year-old corpsman out there on how to become a leader.
What would you tell them?
I know you've given talks on these things before.
Well, I would first have them examine to be sure that they want to be a leader.
Each individual should be sure that they are willing to give up
what you give up when you get out in front.
You're going to have to make decisions.
Some of them are going to be unpopular.
You're the boss and people won't associate with you.
And those that do associate with you,
The other people think that they're trying to polish the apple and what have you.
So it's rather a lonely type of life at the man at the top, but it's not crowded at the top at all.
And I've found that probably only 10% of the individuals, even the officers, are willing to be out in front, because if you're out in front, why is everybody looking at you?
I mean your boss is looking at you and everybody below is looking at you.
So you have to be sure that you want to do that.
And the other thing, the next thing I think is if your family life is you have to live
